Kenya is safe for tourists planning to visit ahead of the August 8 General Election, Tourism CS Najib Balala (pictured) has said. &ldquo;The high season has started and already we have international tourists coming to watch wildebeest migration at the Maasai Mara. We want them to feel free and secure, and to enjoy each and every second of their holiday,&rdquo; Balala said.He was speaking on Thursday at Diani Reef Beach Hotel and Spa during the 15th Annual Tourism Symposium titled Sustainable Tourism for Development.Balala said the government will ensure a free and fair election to safeguard tourists and to boost economy. &ldquo;We will not sit back and watch young boys ruin the reputation of the Coast region, which will scare away tourists, who are a major source of income,&rdquo; the CS said. Gangs have been causing trouble in some areas.